# The Relative Efficiency (RE) compares the Randomized Complete Block Design (RCB) to a Completely Randomized Design (CRD). It helps determine whether blocking effectively reduces variance and improves precision.
# RE > 1 means that the blocking was effectiveâ€”the RCB design provides more precise estimates than a CRD.
# RE = 5.19 suggests that the RCB design is over 5 times more efficient than the CRD in reducing variability and improving the accuracy of detecting treatment effects.
contrasts(drug$dose) <- contr.poly(5)
library(daewr)
data("drug")
model2 <- aov(rate ~ rat + dose, data = drug)
summary(model2)
# The ANOVA table shows that rat has a highly significant effect (p < 0.001), meaning there are large individual differences between rats.
# However, even after considering these differences, the dose effect is still highly significant (p < 0.001).
# This means that the treatment (dose) significantly affects lever pull rate, beyond just the differences between individual rats.
(1.6685 + 0.3006)/(5*(10-1))
(10330 + 10509)/(4*(3-1))
